title: Parametric Linear Bearing with Optional Split

description.text:
I made this tonight since my X-Axis bearings were shot and carving a groove in my rods.  My printer is working seemingly better than ever with these in place of the steel on steel bearings they replaced.  
I printed these at half the "height" of the originals for now thinking this would decrease friction, but I might have that exactly wrong.  Longer bearings may yield less friction since it distributes the load over a larger area.  Try for yourself and please let me know what you think.  
At first I printed these solid (no split) which would have required me to take apart my whole X-Axis but then it occurred to me to just split them.  I pushed my old bearings off to the sides and slipped these in.  It's working great.  
I've never bought a set of bearings, but these are clearly cheaper and a lot easier to replace than the originals too.  
Note: I'd recommend some lubrication between the bearing and the linear rods.

  • Using a heat pen, carefully heat the section over the edge of the table. Bend the piece until you have a 90 degree angle. Allow it to cool before un-clamping.

Notes: (type misc. notes here)

We used blender to design our thing. We started with a cube then we extruded it to get a baseline of what we wanted. Then we used a cylinder, and did something called Boolean to make the curves we wanted. After making the curves we went back and fixed up all the mistakes and problems we had.

We learned how to use blender, and you will too! Nobody without a high school edumucation or a very skilled blenderer. You should have an understandin' of how to use the Boolean feature. For the steps, I started out with a cube, I extruded three out of the four sides so it looked like an upside down T. After that I made a cut at the top to make a new face. Then I extruded those, and repeated the process at the end of the new part. Then I had a baseline for what I wanted it to look like. Next, I created a cylinder and widened it to match the curve of the actual T. Then, I moved the cylinder into the corner. Next, I went to the tool bar on the right and went into the modifier section and selected Boolean under the "Add Modifier" drop down. Once the Boolean modifier has been added, select the difference operation. In order to cut out of the T and have faces, select the baseline T in the grid, then make sure the cylinder is in the correct position. Finally while the T is selected on the grid, select the cylinder under the "Object:" drop down and apply. Repeat this for each corner and adjust the size of the cylinder to match the bottom corners. Finally I went back and checked the thing for problems or anything messed up about the thing. The final product if you followed the instructions correctly should be the Tennessee Volunteers Power T.

title: Z axis mod for Reprappro mendel mono or tricolour

description.text: The M5 nuts on the Z axis have a small amount of play (~0.5mm), and if the X axis belt tension compensation screws (at the idler end) aren't absolutely perfectly adjusted (I still don't know where that sweet spot is) the Z axis hangs up on the thread, which can lead to Z axis inaccuracy. This mod adds a second nut at the motor end to remove the play.

• After printing it, remove the Z axis motor at the X axis motor end (see the pic) and unscrew the threaded rod. put a second M5 nut in the nut case (leave the spring where it is for the moment)

  • screw the rod through the nut case and into the original (lower) M5 nut, leave some space for the nut case to move up and down a bit.

  • Thoroughly clean the flange on the nut case and the top of the X axis motor mount with acetone or MEK. Alternatively, I used a superglue primer.

  • Superglue the nut case in place, making sure there is space around the threaded rod.

  • Once the glue has set, unscrew the rod and move the spring from its original position to the slot in the nut case.

  • Screw the rod through the upper and lower nuts. Make sure the spring is slightly compressed such that there is a small gap above the upper nut when you let the rod go (0.5mm is good)

  • Reassemble the Z axis motor and realign the Z axis.
    • NOTES: After using this for a while I started having problems with the bed going out of level. After much investigation I found that it wasn't the bed at all, but the Z Axis motor at the X drive end losing steps. It turns out that you only need a very small amount of pressure on the second nut to take up the slack. Because I didn't have another spring, I used the one originally supplied with the MonoMendel kit. The result was that as the nuts get dirty, the drag on the Z axis motor increases until it starts losing steps. I'm still looking for a fix, but there are some things to try:
  • Use a low viscosity lubricant such as sewing machine oil
  • From time to time disassemble the Z axis and thoroughly clean the screws and nuts
  • Make sure the X axis belt tension screws are adjusted to allow the Z axis to slide freely on the rods.

comments.text: Just my 2 cents: The bushings supplied with the printer kit are not really that great at allowing the X carriage arm to slide freely. I reprinted this part so it took proper linear bearings. The Z axis m8 nuts are a bad choice too ... The ones that came with the kit wear easily, just take them out and have a look at the inside thread, after a short time mine were showing almost smooth on the inside. I replaced these with brass m8 nuts, you would think that these will smooth out quicker but with proper lubrication and care these have outlasted the original m8s.
comments.author: oddy992

comments.text: I can't emphasize this enough.  Whether you have this mod installed or not, YOU MUST LUBRICATE THE Z SCREWS!  Any screw thread that runs dry will wear out in short order, and as junkelslitsy has found, the rods will eventually get worn to the point that they bind.

title: prusa i3 Zonestar p802 z axis upgrade

description.text:
This version is no-longer being maintained
please use the V2 linked below as it is soo much better.
Even if you only use the updated top plates it's still so much better. V2 is here http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1470886
many improvements.
new parts include updated top plates with more adjust-ability for belt length, and a 18t stepper pulley and updated 36t pulleys for the z lead screws (so a 2x improvement in torque)
you may wish to refer back to here for construction tips and parts, as V2 is very similar (with the belt setup) old version please move on to V2 (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1470886) if you can as it is much better.. This is a z axis upgrade for my zonestar p802 I3,
this features a top plate with a stepper motor mount, 608 bearing hole for the z lead-screws and slots for idlers, to adjust to a standard length of belt. This has fixed the issue of having to re-align the x stage of my i3 each time I wanted to print. V1 tweak
I had a problem with the blank shaft connector rubbing the z guides, so have updated the part to V2 and made them a bit smaller in diameter. for this you will need the following parts, 2x 8mm toothed pulleys
1x 5mm toothed pulley,
1 belt (GT2 2mm Timing Belt 976mm x 6mm (488 teeth) )
2-3x idler pulleys
3x idler standoffs
2x 8mm shaft couplers (to clamp underside of Z lead-screw) - now V2
2x base mount (to stop 8mm shaft from falling though, this replaces the bottom mounted stepper motors)
7x 608 ball bearings
M8x50 bolts (for idlers)
M8 studding (for re-enforcing)
M8 nuts (I used a mixture of Nyloc and regular)
M8 washers
M4 nuts and M4 grub screws (to grip shafts form pulleys)
misc M3 nits/bolts for belt tensioner Future enhancements:
I may make a bottom bearing for the z lead-screws (which is why there is an 8mm hole directly beneath them) but if they are not needed then I won't bother.

This is an alternative carriage for the 20x20 mini Kossel. It is intended to be used in conjunction with delrin/pom profile sliders from the likes of Motedis http://www.motedis.co.uk/shop/Dynamics-Basics/Profile-Glide/Slider-B-Type-Slot-6::99999563.html. The sliders cost about £2.10 ($3.25 each), and are significantly cheaper than any other solution I have seen so far. The delrin slider is designed to be used for moving panels of glass enclosed within 20x20mm profile aluminium frames along other lengths of 20x20 profile, so the hard part of making an item, with the correct profile, that will not wear significantly over time has already been taken care of. The sliders are also available for other sizes of aluminium profile, so there is no reason why this design cannot be scaled up for a bigger delta printer, or for other similar uses. The carriage attaches directly to the slider with three M4x20mm cap head set screws, SAE screws of a similar size could also be used. The sliders need to be drilled and tapped, as they only come with pilot holes pre drilled, so the carriages will work with any similar sized cap head screw. You can see the full writeup of this item on my blog http://zebethyalprusa.blogspot.co.uk/2015/04/mini-kossel-build-part-2-frame-again.html I have included the stl file as well as the sketchup file it was produced from.
